    AI Guidance

    AI Guidance

    AI Guidance

    The guidance sections below define the minimum disclosure and documentation standards for the use of artificial intelligence (AI) in research processes, data analysis, and scholarly communications/publications. Professional standards in your specific field(s) may dictate additional requirements.

    Important

    All research, including research that is not reviewed by a formal oversight committee such as the IRB and/or the IACUC, is still subject to and must be conducted in accordance with the GSU AI Policy. Particular attention should be paid to ensure that the principles of bias, accuracy and intentional and unintentional misuse in the GSU AI Policy are taken into account.

    Office of Research Guidance for Use of AI in Research at GSU

    Purpose

    The primary purpose of this guidance is to provide a framework for the responsible and ethical integration of AI technologies in research, ensuring they augment and enrich the learning experience rather than replace genuine knowledge transference and critical thinking. GSU views AI as a tool to be used at the discretion and direction of educators and authorized personnel, not as a mandatory or compulsory element in every classroom or operation. This policy aims to ensure consistent standards and best practices while allowing for institutional flexibility to meet specific needs.

    Guiding Principles

    Refer to the GSU AI Policy for additional information.

    Researchers bear significant responsibilities regarding AI use:

    • All GenAI use in research must be clearly identified and properly cited according to faculty guidelines. Failure to disclose AI use may be considered a research integrity violation. Refer to GSU ORIAs Statement on the Responsible Use of Artificial Intelligence in Research. Researchers are expected to act in accord with accepted research integrity practices of their professional research community and abide by journal-specific requirements for disclosure of GenAI use.
    • Outputs from GenAI must be verified by the researcher(s) for accuracy and attribution before use in research and research communications and publications.
    • The Principal Investigator (PI) is ultimately responsible for any AI use in research, including for verifying the accuracy and attribution of all use and research outputs generated by AI and must properly disclose the AI methods and tools used.
    • Users are accountable for the accuracy and freedom from errors or biases in AI-generated content.
    • Any mistakes generated by GenAI and subsequently used in publications, grants, or other outputs are the sole responsibility of the author and may be considered "knowing" or "reckless" use for purposes of research misconduct investigations or potentially deemed fraudulent for federal grant applications.
    • Faculty must follow the guidelines of appropriate oversight committees (IRB, IACUC, IBC, etc.) regarding AI use in creating scholarly and/or publishable materials and research.
    • Researchers should be transparent about their GenAI tool use and prepared to answer questions about its contribution to materials.
    • Researchers must not input identifiable, personal, private, or HIPAA, FERPA, Common Rule, or Export Control protected information into an unsecure GenAI system.
    • Researchers should exercise caution when using AI as it raises research integrity concerns, including unintentional plagiarism. Implications for research integrity violations (fabrication, falsification, and plagiarism) are significant, as GenAI can consistently fabricate facts and citations (hallucination).

    Intellectual Property Considerations

    • Submitting information to a generative AI tool may relinquish rights to control future use of intellectual property. More information about the IP considerations of AI use is available.
    • Inputting potential IP into generative AI creates a risk that the input may be used to train and improve the generative AI, potentially making it publicly discoverable if references in future outputs for other users.
    • Materials prepared using generative AI tools may not be eligible for intellectual property rights if there is insufficient direct human involvement in their development.
    • Documentation of human contributions to AI-assisted projects may prove helpful in establishing authorship or inventorship for purposes of obtaining intellectual property protection.
    • Defined guidelines surrounding the use of Gen AI may help to protect intellectual property and novel research findings.
    • Outputs and works generated by generative AI may invoke issues of copyright infringement if similar to copyrighted works.
    • The use of AI technology must comply with applicable intellectual property or other legal restrictions.
    • The legal implications of using AI in the development of intellectual property are part of a complex landscape that continues to evolve and therefore requires careful consideration and documentation of AI use.
    • The legal landscape surrounding AI and intellectual property may vary across different countries and jurisdictions.

    Related Policies and Procedures

    • GSU Data Classification Policy and Standards: For determining the classification level of data.
    • GSU Policy on Academic Honesty: For addressing violations related to AI use.
    • GSU Student Code of Conduct: For disciplinary actions.
    • GSU Intellectual Property Policy: For considerations related to ownership and use of AI-generated content.
    • USG IT Handbook Companion Guide: For general AI solution deployment considerations and responsible AI principles.
    • USG Academic & Student Affairs Handbook: For standards, procedures, and guidelines.
    • GSU AI Literacy Resources: To be developed for foundational knowledge, skills, and values in AI use.(resources pending)
    • GSU AI Tool Registry/Approved List: To provide information on approved AI technology and any respective limitations.(resource pending)
    • NIH Notice NOT-OD-23-149: The Use of Generative Artificial Intelligence Technologies is Prohibited for the NIH Peer Review Process
    • NIH Frequently Asked Questions (FAQs) Use of Generative AI in Peer Review
    • NIH Notice NOT-OD-25-132:Supporting Fairness and Originality in NIH Research Applications
    • GSU Office of Research Integrity Assurance Statement on the Responsible Use of Artificial Intelligence in Research

    Related Guidelines and Standards

    For questions or to provide feedback on this guidance, please contact [email protected].

    Statement on the Responsible Use of Artificial Intelligence in Research from the GSU Office of Research Integrity Assurance

    Purpose

    This statement establishes principles and expectations for the responsible use of artificial intelligence (AI) tools in research at Georgia State University. The goal is to ensure that AI technologies enhance research integrity rather than compromise it, particularly with respect to avoiding Falsification, Fabrication, and Plagiarism (FFP) as defined by federal Research Misconduct regulations (42 C.F.R. 93.103).

    Scope

    These principles apply to all faculty, staff, students, and collaborators engaged in research activities at GSU, including those using AI tools for data analysis, writing, literature review, image generation, translation, or other research-related tasks.

    Best Practices

    1. Avoiding Falsification and Fabrication

    Researchers must not use AI tools to generate, alter, or manipulate data, images, or results in a way that misrepresents the research record. This includes:

    • Generating synthetic data and presenting it as empirical data.
    • Using AI to fill in gaps in datasets without justification and documentation.
    • Altering figures or images via AI tools without clear disclosure.
    • Presenting AI-generated analyses or visualizations as independently verified.

    Example: Using an AI tool to simulate a chart of results and including it in a manuscript without stating it was generated synthetically may constitute Falsification.

    2. Avoiding Plagiarism

    Researchers must ensure that AI-generated text, code, or content is original or properly attributed. When AI is used for drafting or content generation:

    • Researchers remain responsible for ensuring originality.
    • Proper attribution must be given to all sources.
    • AI-generated summaries must be verified and cited appropriately.

    Example: Submitting a grant proposal containing AI-generated text that closely paraphrases published work without citation may constitute Plagiarism.

    3. Transparency and Accountability

    Researchers must disclose the use of AI when it materially contributes to research design, data generation, or writing. This includes:

    • Identifying the AI tools used.
    • Describing how AI tools contributed to the work.
    • Retaining records of AI prompts and outputs when feasible.

    Note: AI tools (e.g., ChatGPT, Gemini, Claude) cannot be credited as authors.

    4. Training and Oversight

    Principal Investigators (PIs) are responsible for ensuring that all members of their research teams understand and adhere to these expectations. The Office of Research Integrity Assurance is available to provide training and guidance.

    Violations

    Improper use of AI that results in FFP or other research integrity violations will be investigated under GSUs Research Misconduct Policy and may result in disciplinary action. Violations may also be reported to external funding agencies in accordance with federal requirements.

    Contact

    If you have any questions or need feedback on this guidance, contact the Office of Research Integrity Assurance at [email protected].

    For additional guidance on AI tools and using AI, please visit the Using AI@GSU Website.

    References

    • 42 C.F.R. Part 93 Public Health Service Policies on Research Misconduct
    • NIH Guidance on AI Tools in Peer Review
    • NSF Responsible Conduct of Research
    • GSU Research Misconduct Policy
    Guidance for Responsible and Ethical Use of AI in Human Subjects Research

    Purpose

    The use of AI is becoming increasingly prevalent in the field of human subjects research, from researchers use of AI platforms as a tool (e.g., for transcribing and organizing data) to a growing body of research that considers the impact of AIs use in various settings. GSUs Institutional Review Board (IRB) does not prohibit the use of AI as a research methodology or topic; however, its use must be undertaken responsibly and in a manner that upholds the rights, safety and welfare of human participants in research.

    Research Procedures

    When researchers plans involve AI interacting directly with human subjects, this must be disclosed in IRB applications and approved in advance.

    Using AI for automated decision-makingthat will impact interactions/interventions with human subjects, absent an intermediary review by a member of the research team, requiresextreme caution; see the GSU AI Policy.

    Researchers should be prepared to assess and mitigate biases in AI-generated content and IRB applications should clearly identify when subject-facing outputs or responses will be AI-generated.

    Confidentiality

    Sharing identifiable research data with a third-party AI platform poses confidentiality risks to human research subjects.

    Researchers' plans for collecting, storing, and sharing human research data must be disclosed in IRB applications and approved in advance, including researchers planned use of AI tools in these contexts.

    Researchers may not submit any data that directly identifies an individual, or is classified by the university as Sensitive or Confidential, into an AI tool not supported by Georgia State. Examples would include submitting recordings of focus group discussions to generate transcripts or uploading individually identifiable data to perform analyses.

    Any data set including information that can indirectly identify an individual may not be submitted to an AI tool not supported by Georgia State. An example would be a data set that includes the combination of major, GPA, and academic term for each research subject.

    See Georgia States Data Classification Standard for more information on personally identifiable information and data classification.

    Informed Consent

    The use of AI must be disclosed to research participants in accordance with IRB requirements for informed consent. AI-related information that may be relevant to subject informed consent includes (not an exhaustive list): the nature and purpose of AI tools used in the study; how data will be shared with AI-based platforms; and potential risks to the participants of AI, including risks related to confidentiality and algorithmic bias or misuse.

    The GSU IRB Manual details information and elements that must be included in the informed consent process/documents as well as defined conditions under which waivers or alterations of informed consent may be granted.

    IRB Submissions

    Prior to submission to the IRB, researchers should carefully review AI-generated responses to IRB application prompts and AI-generated supporting documents. Using AI to prepare IRB proposals has led to internal inconsistencies within applications, and between applications and supporting documents; this prolongs the IRB review process. Researchers should use their own language to prepare clear and concise responses and materials. The Principal Investigator is ultimately responsible for the content and quality of any application made to the IRB.

    Contact

    For questions or to provide feedback on this guidance, please get in touch with the IRB at [email protected].

    For additional guidance on AI tools and using AI, please visit the Using AI@GSU Website.
